The Ukraine on the way to Europe
"East is east and west is west, and they will never meet," said Rudyard Kipling once.
The Ukraine lies undeniably in the east, but in the east of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path to that goal was, however, not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It goes without saying to me that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties the Ukraine has had in joining Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural regions were practically paralyzed by outdated machinery parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We have completely botched the reforms on our own.
For this reason, we often wanted to import proven concepts from the West—private property, free market economy, strict adherence to human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy—in a modified form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the Parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is something like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has now gained momentum, even though we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
One can see this on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to cross the street in safety from reckless drivers).
In Kyiv there is now a vibrant café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the Internet in Internet cafés.
But these are only the sentimental digressions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober gaze of the professional politician, which I am, sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, a development has taken place from a total rejection of reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
At first, the reform of the state provoked an antagonistic mood among both civil servants and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "F-style" reform: the state must shrink, people assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one considered that countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by cutting the red pen led us to the second stage of our reform process.
Slowly, the state was reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
By this, the work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At the beginning, the authority entrusted to these new areas was somewhat too broad to effectively carry out their work.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes get annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (even though reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists – of which there are still too many among us – can afford to adopt an indifferent attitude toward a more efficient state.
The taming of our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
The Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial cannot possibly admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse to have to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best of what others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians had to realize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even more ill, but the recent elections, which have undermined the Communists' dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalised individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, difficult journey toward Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
